WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.562 --> 00:00:02.020
LISA LEE: Good
afternoon, everyone.

00:00:02.020 --> 00:00:04.880
And welcome to another exciting
event here at Tech Corners.

00:00:04.880 --> 00:00:08.230
And I want to give a
huge shout-out to Regina.

00:00:08.230 --> 00:00:09.070
Where is she?

00:00:09.070 --> 00:00:09.570
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:09.570 --> 00:00:11.810
Thank you, Regina,
for coordinating all

00:00:11.810 --> 00:00:14.022
your hard work that
goes into this.

00:00:14.022 --> 00:00:14.980
I mean it took an hour.

00:00:14.980 --> 00:00:18.690
But it takes her weeks, I'm
sure, to put this all together.

00:00:18.690 --> 00:00:19.484
I'm Lisa Lee.

00:00:19.484 --> 00:00:21.400
And I'm really incredibly
excited to introduce

00:00:21.400 --> 00:00:25.770
Luboc Azria, the chief creative
officer at BCBG Max Azria

00:00:25.770 --> 00:00:29.150
Group, a global fashion house,
with one of the hottest labels

00:00:29.150 --> 00:00:31.400
and brands in the
fashion industry today,

00:00:31.400 --> 00:00:33.420
that styles everyday
modern women like you

00:00:33.420 --> 00:00:37.040
and I, in the contemporary
price point range,

00:00:37.040 --> 00:00:39.530
to supermodels and
Hollywood celebrities.

00:00:39.530 --> 00:00:41.970
She joined the company
as a designer in 1991

00:00:41.970 --> 00:00:44.540
and was named creative
director in 1996.

00:00:44.540 --> 00:00:47.370
Under her influence-- and
I've been told that she's also

00:00:47.370 --> 00:00:50.100
known as the muse
of the company--

00:00:50.100 --> 00:00:55.100
it evolved from an emerging
line to one of America's leading

00:00:55.100 --> 00:00:57.980
design houses, including being
the first American design house

00:00:57.980 --> 00:01:02.040
to absorb the esteemed French
fashion house, Herve Leger.

00:01:02.040 --> 00:01:03.770
She's joining us
here today at Google

00:01:03.770 --> 00:01:08.350
to share an exclusive screening
of the 2015 Spring Runway Show

00:01:08.350 --> 00:01:10.350
and to provide it with
some personal commentary.

00:01:10.350 --> 00:01:11.040
LUBOC AZRIA: Absolutely.

00:01:11.040 --> 00:01:12.498
LISA LEE: And if
that isn't enough,

00:01:12.498 --> 00:01:14.150
I'm really impressed
that she's also

00:01:14.150 --> 00:01:16.320
a mother of six,
three [INAUDIBLE].

00:01:16.320 --> 00:01:17.274
[CHEERS]

00:01:18.060 --> 00:01:20.380
So you'll have to tell
us your secret and how

00:01:20.380 --> 00:01:21.720
you balance all that.

00:01:21.720 --> 00:01:23.880
And obviously, you
look so beautiful.

00:01:23.880 --> 00:01:25.030
So welcome to Google.

00:01:25.030 --> 00:01:26.080
LUBOC AZRIA: Thank you.

00:01:26.080 --> 00:01:28.070
Hi everyone.

00:01:28.070 --> 00:01:29.786
How's everybody doing today?

00:01:29.786 --> 00:01:30.411
AUDIENCE: Good.

00:01:30.411 --> 00:01:31.161
LUBOC AZRIA: Good.

00:01:31.161 --> 00:01:33.420
Well, I'm very happy to be here.

00:01:33.420 --> 00:01:34.780
So it's very exciting.

00:01:34.780 --> 00:01:36.660
And I think we
should start, right?

00:01:36.660 --> 00:01:37.320
LISA LEE: Yes.

00:01:37.320 --> 00:01:39.329
So really just to start
off so that everyone

00:01:39.329 --> 00:01:40.870
gets to know you a
little bit better,

00:01:40.870 --> 00:01:42.828
if you can tell us a
little bit about yourself,

00:01:42.828 --> 00:01:44.550
and some of your
passions, and how

00:01:44.550 --> 00:01:48.060
that translates into your
personal style, and the work

00:01:48.060 --> 00:01:49.590
that you do?

00:01:49.590 --> 00:01:55.570
LUBOC AZRIA: So I'm
originally from Ukraine, Kiev.

00:01:55.570 --> 00:02:02.950
How many of you actually
were not born here?

00:02:02.950 --> 00:02:04.290
OK.

00:02:04.290 --> 00:02:05.782
So you'll love this story.

00:02:05.782 --> 00:02:08.479
So briefly, I was born in Kiev.

00:02:08.479 --> 00:02:12.230
And I think that your
cultural background sometimes

00:02:12.230 --> 00:02:13.410
defines you.

00:02:13.410 --> 00:02:17.900
I think when I was
growing up, I was

00:02:17.900 --> 00:02:19.720
meant to be a prima ballerina.

00:02:19.720 --> 00:02:23.247
So from the age of
4 and 1/2 to 5--

00:02:23.247 --> 00:02:25.330
actually, I was about 5
years old, where they come

00:02:25.330 --> 00:02:29.010
and they test you, how limber
you are and everything else.

00:02:29.010 --> 00:02:30.600
Your life is determined.

00:02:30.600 --> 00:02:35.210
And so I trained in-- there's
like little satellite groups

00:02:35.210 --> 00:02:36.470
of Kirov ballet.

00:02:36.470 --> 00:02:38.710
So that's how my
initial training was.

00:02:38.710 --> 00:02:41.200
But my true passion
was always art.

00:02:41.200 --> 00:02:43.080
And I loved drawing
and painting.

00:02:43.080 --> 00:02:45.330
And I took art classes.

00:02:45.330 --> 00:02:53.390
Anyway, in the 1980s, Brezhnev
signed an agreement with Israel

00:02:53.390 --> 00:02:55.140
to let the Jews out.

00:02:55.140 --> 00:02:56.040
I'm Jewish.

00:02:56.040 --> 00:02:58.180
And there was a huge
prosecution against Jews.

00:02:58.180 --> 00:03:00.440
We couldn't attend universities.

00:03:00.440 --> 00:03:03.369
We couldn't actually
get higher jobs.

00:03:03.369 --> 00:03:04.660
We couldn't do a lot of things.

00:03:04.660 --> 00:03:09.550
So my parents were
lucky enough to leave.

00:03:09.550 --> 00:03:13.550
And so we immigrated
to the United States.

00:03:13.550 --> 00:03:18.460
And the place that we end
up in is San Antonio, Texas.

00:03:18.460 --> 00:03:19.360
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:20.810 --> 00:03:23.590
Of all the places, it
was San Antonio, Texas.

00:03:23.590 --> 00:03:26.240
And so I really started
growing up there.

00:03:26.240 --> 00:03:29.600
And I have to say that I never
thought of fashion as fashion,

00:03:29.600 --> 00:03:32.640
like I didn't know the
fashion industry existed.

00:03:32.640 --> 00:03:34.750
In the former
Soviet Union, it was

00:03:34.750 --> 00:03:37.670
like everybody was wearing the
same thing over and over again.

00:03:37.670 --> 00:03:41.090
So I didn't really realize
that there was a fashion world.

00:03:41.090 --> 00:03:45.660
All I wanted to do was to
be an art history professor.

00:03:45.660 --> 00:03:46.920
So I studied art.

00:03:46.920 --> 00:03:48.400
I was really
passionate about it.

00:03:48.400 --> 00:03:52.120
And obviously, I danced
as well, on the side.

00:03:52.120 --> 00:03:58.000
And so in 1986, there was
an oil crisis in Texas.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:03:59.600
And a lot of people
lost their jobs.

00:03:59.600 --> 00:04:01.836
And so we moved
from San Antonio,

00:04:01.836 --> 00:04:03.460
Texas-- and I know
it's a lot of story.

00:04:03.460 --> 00:04:08.370
But there's a good point to it.

00:04:08.370 --> 00:04:11.680
So we moved from San Antonio,
Texas to Los Angeles.

00:04:11.680 --> 00:04:13.450
And I remember being in LA.

00:04:13.450 --> 00:04:15.000
And I am 18 years old.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:16.550
And I don't know
what my future is.

00:04:16.550 --> 00:04:18.680
All I know is that
I want to be in art.

00:04:18.680 --> 00:04:21.370
I want to be in something
that really has--

00:04:21.370 --> 00:04:23.930
the possibilities are endless.

00:04:23.930 --> 00:04:26.180
And I can create something
that can make a difference.

00:04:26.180 --> 00:04:28.350
So anyway, I am in Los Angeles.

00:04:28.350 --> 00:04:30.340
And it's two weeks
after I arrived there.

00:04:30.340 --> 00:04:32.760
And I decided to go shopping.

00:04:32.760 --> 00:04:35.040
And I went on
Wilshire Boulevard.

00:04:35.040 --> 00:04:36.556
So I'm just walking on Wilshire.

00:04:36.556 --> 00:04:38.430
I don't know if you
guys, any of you know LA?

00:04:38.430 --> 00:04:41.390
But it's like a-- anyway,
there's large department stores

00:04:41.390 --> 00:04:41.890
there.

00:04:41.890 --> 00:04:44.440
So I was walking by one
of the department stores.

00:04:44.440 --> 00:04:48.440
And there was the most
beautiful dress in the window.

00:04:48.440 --> 00:04:50.190
I mean the dress
was so stunning.

00:04:50.190 --> 00:04:52.942
And I decided that I'm
just going to go in.

00:04:52.942 --> 00:04:54.650
I've never been to
this department store.

00:04:54.650 --> 00:04:56.880
But I'm going to go
in and try it on.

00:04:59.500 --> 00:05:02.290
As I walk in, I ask for the
dress that in the window.

00:05:02.290 --> 00:05:05.640
And the sales person there said,
well, it's on the second floor.

00:05:05.640 --> 00:05:07.130
We having a new trunk show.

00:05:07.130 --> 00:05:08.300
They gave me the dress.

00:05:08.300 --> 00:05:13.310
And so I went into the
dressing room, put it on.

00:05:13.310 --> 00:05:14.355
It was stunning.

00:05:14.355 --> 00:05:17.410
It was the most beautiful
thing I've ever had on.

00:05:17.410 --> 00:05:19.400
I started twirling in the dress.

00:05:19.400 --> 00:05:26.372
I mean just having a good time,
until I saw the price tag.

00:05:26.372 --> 00:05:28.330
And the price-- now,
remember, this is in 1986.

00:05:28.330 --> 00:05:31.820
So the price tag was $3,000.

00:05:31.820 --> 00:05:34.464
And I remember my
car was $1,500.

00:05:34.464 --> 00:05:35.440
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:35.440 --> 00:05:37.490
So that it was
not going to work.

00:05:37.490 --> 00:05:41.010
And at that moment,
as I was looking

00:05:41.010 --> 00:05:44.740
at myself in the mirror, at
that moment that pain hit me.

00:05:44.740 --> 00:05:47.630
The pain was that
I'm not good enough.

00:05:47.630 --> 00:05:48.530
What am I doing here?

00:05:48.530 --> 00:05:52.390
People like me don't
wear clothes like that.

00:05:52.390 --> 00:05:54.390
Really, like all
the negative things

00:05:54.390 --> 00:05:56.920
just started flowing through me.

00:05:56.920 --> 00:05:59.640
And I started crying, but
sort of tearing up more.

00:05:59.640 --> 00:06:01.260
And then I pulled
myself together.

00:06:01.260 --> 00:06:04.760
I looked in the mirror
and I said, if I ever,

00:06:04.760 --> 00:06:06.710
ever become a
designer, I will never

00:06:06.710 --> 00:06:08.460
make clothes that
are that expensive.

00:06:08.460 --> 00:06:12.550
I will never make a
woman feel this pain.

00:06:12.550 --> 00:06:15.570
Nobody deserves
to feel this pain.

00:06:15.570 --> 00:06:16.830
And I made that promise.

00:06:16.830 --> 00:06:18.571
I took off my dress.

00:06:18.571 --> 00:06:21.070
Now, again, I didn't know it
that I wanted to be a designer.

00:06:21.070 --> 00:06:22.702
I had no idea.

00:06:22.702 --> 00:06:24.410
Took off the dress,
put it on the hanger,

00:06:24.410 --> 00:06:29.870
zipped it up, thanked the
sales people, and left.

00:06:29.870 --> 00:06:31.740
Next day, believe it
or not-- not next day,

00:06:31.740 --> 00:06:35.430
but like two days after,
a fashion school came in.

00:06:35.430 --> 00:06:38.760
And I filled out,
saying I liked fashion.

00:06:38.760 --> 00:06:39.830
I like this.

00:06:39.830 --> 00:06:43.570
My whole life from that moment
on-- it's like in that movie

00:06:43.570 --> 00:06:47.020
when you make a promise,
everything, like, starts

00:06:47.020 --> 00:06:50.750
opening for you, everything
in my life from that point on.

00:06:50.750 --> 00:06:53.475
I went to fashion school-- well,
I filled out a application.

00:06:53.475 --> 00:06:55.600
The next thing I knew, I
was in the fashion school.

00:06:55.600 --> 00:06:58.020
The next thing I
knew, I had a job.

00:06:58.020 --> 00:07:02.240
It was just everything
was just incredibly--

00:07:02.240 --> 00:07:05.360
it's like my destiny was
created at that moment.

00:07:05.360 --> 00:07:07.670
And I don't know if any of
you had that experience.

00:07:07.670 --> 00:07:11.502
But it's just sort of, you do
thing and you make a promise.

00:07:11.502 --> 00:07:13.210
And then everything
in your life changes.

00:07:13.210 --> 00:07:16.180
And so to me,
fashion represents--

00:07:16.180 --> 00:07:17.577
it's not just about clothes.

00:07:17.577 --> 00:07:19.035
But it's about
making a difference.

00:07:19.035 --> 00:07:20.690
Do you know I'm saying?

00:07:20.690 --> 00:07:23.390
I believe that if you make a
woman feel and look beautiful,

00:07:23.390 --> 00:07:25.340
she can make this
world a better place.

00:07:25.340 --> 00:07:26.850
LISA LEE: So it looks like
it all crystallized for you.

00:07:26.850 --> 00:07:27.600
LUBOC AZRIA: Yeah.

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:28.230
Yeah.

00:07:28.230 --> 00:07:29.900
LISA LEE: And so
from that point on,

00:07:29.900 --> 00:07:33.580
how does that experience--
how does that translate

00:07:33.580 --> 00:07:38.230
to your designs today, and
the labels, and what you do?

00:07:38.230 --> 00:07:40.360
LUBOC AZRIA: Well, it
translates in every way.

00:07:40.360 --> 00:07:43.170
I mean until this day, I
fit every single piece.

00:07:43.170 --> 00:07:46.042
I also kind of realized
that-- for example, I

00:07:46.042 --> 00:07:48.250
don't know if you know
anything about making clothes.

00:07:48.250 --> 00:07:52.040
But you can take a dress that
you're wearing, for example.

00:07:54.940 --> 00:07:56.560
You can take a dress
like this and you

00:07:56.560 --> 00:07:58.830
can have it 10 times
more expensive,

00:07:58.830 --> 00:08:01.922
if you don't think about the
marker, and the fabrication,

00:08:01.922 --> 00:08:02.630
and how it moves.

00:08:02.630 --> 00:08:05.360
So we really engineer
everything to give you

00:08:05.360 --> 00:08:08.160
the best price that we can.

00:08:08.160 --> 00:08:11.861
Because I believe that a
woman has to feel good.

00:08:11.861 --> 00:08:14.140
Most designers
don't appreciate, I

00:08:14.140 --> 00:08:16.820
think, the consumer and
their spending power.

00:08:16.820 --> 00:08:19.440
Or their knowledge, I
think I would want to say.

00:08:19.440 --> 00:08:21.560
Like, women are so much smarter.

00:08:21.560 --> 00:08:24.390
You don't have to be in fashion
business to understand fashion.

00:08:24.390 --> 00:08:25.570
You don't have to be.

00:08:25.570 --> 00:08:27.420
You know what you like.

00:08:27.420 --> 00:08:29.240
And that's the most
important thing.

00:08:29.240 --> 00:08:32.110
Fashion is about
connecting with something.

00:08:32.110 --> 00:08:35.340
So what I do is I create
clothes that I want to wear.

00:08:35.340 --> 00:08:35.870
I'm a woman.

00:08:35.870 --> 00:08:38.409
It's so interesting because
in design, we always

00:08:38.409 --> 00:08:39.860
think that we're somebody else.

00:08:39.860 --> 00:08:40.525
But we're not.

00:08:40.525 --> 00:08:41.760
We're women.

00:08:41.760 --> 00:08:44.990
The majority of my
team is also females.

00:08:44.990 --> 00:08:46.550
And then we love what we do.

00:08:46.550 --> 00:08:48.020
We get excited
about the product.

00:08:48.020 --> 00:08:49.860
We can't wait to
wear it ourselves.

00:08:49.860 --> 00:08:52.599
We can't wait to create
a product that we

00:08:52.599 --> 00:08:53.640
respect and want to wear.

00:08:53.640 --> 00:08:55.760
And I think that's
the difference.

00:08:55.760 --> 00:08:57.820
We don't have to
do a lot of things.

00:08:57.820 --> 00:09:03.120
Like I will not create clothes
just to create clothes.

00:09:03.120 --> 00:09:05.880
I really want somebody
wearing it and feeling

00:09:05.880 --> 00:09:08.020
beautiful and elegant.

00:09:08.020 --> 00:09:10.994
And I believe that
you live one life.

00:09:10.994 --> 00:09:12.410
How do you want
to live your life?

00:09:12.410 --> 00:09:13.940
Do you want to
hide behind clothes

00:09:13.940 --> 00:09:15.829
or do you want to
celebrate yourself?

00:09:15.829 --> 00:09:17.620
And if somebody would
take a picture of you

00:09:17.620 --> 00:09:20.780
every single day, would
you be proud of that?

00:09:20.780 --> 00:09:22.200
You know, one life.

00:09:22.200 --> 00:09:25.890
And so to me, that's
very important.

00:09:25.890 --> 00:09:28.400
LISA LEE: That's really,
really inspirational.

00:09:28.400 --> 00:09:30.760
And I think it's something
for people to keep in mind.

00:09:30.760 --> 00:09:33.180
But many of us
here, I'm sure, are

00:09:33.180 --> 00:09:37.180
busy working women, as well
as some of us have kids.

00:09:37.180 --> 00:09:39.220
And so how do you
balance that in terms

00:09:39.220 --> 00:09:42.160
of getting up every day and
to think about yourself first,

00:09:42.160 --> 00:09:45.390
as opposed to your family and
all the other responsibilities?

00:09:45.390 --> 00:09:47.848
LUBOC AZRIA: Well, like I said,
think about yourself first.

00:09:47.848 --> 00:09:51.330
I mean there's a safety
message on the plane.

00:09:51.330 --> 00:09:55.790
It says when the
oxygen mask comes down,

00:09:55.790 --> 00:09:58.962
put it on yourself first,
and then on your children.

00:09:58.962 --> 00:10:00.670
And I think a lot of
women don't do that.

00:10:00.670 --> 00:10:02.400
We tend to take care
of everybody else.

00:10:02.400 --> 00:10:05.070
And then we feel like
something's wrong with us.

00:10:05.070 --> 00:10:08.160
And I think truly taking care
of yourself is so important.

00:10:08.160 --> 00:10:09.660
And I'm not talking
about that idea.

00:10:09.660 --> 00:10:13.900
I'm talking about exercising,
eating right, doing the things

00:10:13.900 --> 00:10:14.540
that you love.

00:10:14.540 --> 00:10:17.900
If you love, for example, I
don't know, roller blading,

00:10:17.900 --> 00:10:18.720
go rollerblade.

00:10:18.720 --> 00:10:22.159
If you love, making jewelry--
if you love anything,

00:10:22.159 --> 00:10:24.450
do you know what I'm saying,
make sure you're doing it.

00:10:24.450 --> 00:10:27.500
Because that is what's
going to satisfy who you are

00:10:27.500 --> 00:10:29.650
and create-- in life,
you don't find yourself.

00:10:29.650 --> 00:10:30.590
You create yourself.

00:10:30.590 --> 00:10:32.840
So create the type of
person that you want to be.

00:10:32.840 --> 00:10:35.450
Most people go around
the world and go, oh,

00:10:35.450 --> 00:10:36.504
this person is so chic.

00:10:36.504 --> 00:10:37.420
She was born that way.

00:10:37.420 --> 00:10:38.820
She wasn't born that way.

00:10:38.820 --> 00:10:40.185
She created herself.

00:10:40.185 --> 00:10:41.380
Do you now what I'm saying?

00:10:41.380 --> 00:10:41.990
She watched.

00:10:41.990 --> 00:10:42.930
She learned.

00:10:42.930 --> 00:10:44.360
And she wanted to
be that person.

00:10:44.360 --> 00:10:46.350
So you become that.

00:10:46.350 --> 00:10:48.360
And I think in terms of
balance and being a mom,

00:10:48.360 --> 00:10:50.270
I think being a mom
is one of the greatest

00:10:50.270 --> 00:10:52.090
gifts in the world.

00:10:52.090 --> 00:10:54.990
I mean those kids are
our greatest teachers.

00:10:54.990 --> 00:10:56.370
And yes, they're tough.

00:10:56.370 --> 00:10:59.330
But that's because they're
trying to find who they are.

00:10:59.330 --> 00:11:02.020
And we just have
to let them grow.

00:11:02.020 --> 00:11:05.240
And I think being friends with
your children is so important.

00:11:05.240 --> 00:11:07.580
I think we're always trying
to tell them what to do.

00:11:07.580 --> 00:11:09.062
And I think, don't.

00:11:09.062 --> 00:11:10.520
I think they'll do
the right thing.

00:11:10.520 --> 00:11:12.350
I notice the less I
tell them what to do,

00:11:12.350 --> 00:11:14.510
the more strict they
are on themselves.

00:11:14.510 --> 00:11:16.650
And I have five
daughters so it's

00:11:16.650 --> 00:11:18.460
kind of like-- it's
a party at the house.

00:11:18.460 --> 00:11:20.460
LISA LEE: So I have to
ask, because my daughter,

00:11:20.460 --> 00:11:22.620
they always decide
what they want to wear.

00:11:22.620 --> 00:11:24.433
And it doesn't always match.

00:11:24.433 --> 00:11:25.400
LUBOC AZRIA: Oh.

00:11:25.400 --> 00:11:26.130
LISA LEE: And you're
like, do you really

00:11:26.130 --> 00:11:27.713
want to put those
two things together?

00:11:27.713 --> 00:11:29.732
So do you let them
experiment and let them?

00:11:29.732 --> 00:11:30.440
LUBOC AZRIA: Yes.

00:11:30.440 --> 00:11:34.560
Actually, I think that's how you
create fashion, by being wrong.

00:11:34.560 --> 00:11:38.400
I don't think fashion should--
I mean we don't match here.

00:11:38.400 --> 00:11:40.009
It's a piece that she likes.

00:11:40.009 --> 00:11:41.800
She probably likes this
great pair of shoes

00:11:41.800 --> 00:11:45.710
and she just wants-- it's about
certain things that they love.

00:11:45.710 --> 00:11:46.810
And let them do it.

00:11:46.810 --> 00:11:49.160
I mean I remember my kids,
I couldn't get them out

00:11:49.160 --> 00:11:53.880
of Halloween costumes
for, like, a year.

00:11:53.880 --> 00:11:56.680
And I said, hey, if you want
to be a superwoman, go ahead,

00:11:56.680 --> 00:11:59.730
every single day, or tutus.

00:11:59.730 --> 00:12:02.580
I mean that was, like, number
one search word, right?

00:12:02.580 --> 00:12:05.380
Or like a item, tutu skirts.

00:12:05.380 --> 00:12:07.260
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:07.260 --> 00:12:11.820
Mine is in the car, with the
bathing suit and flip-flops.

00:12:11.820 --> 00:12:12.580
No.

00:12:12.580 --> 00:12:13.590
But it is.

00:12:13.590 --> 00:12:15.220
Just let her be.

00:12:15.220 --> 00:12:17.210
I mean obviously she
has a reason for it.

00:12:17.210 --> 00:12:18.704
How beautiful is that?

00:12:18.704 --> 00:12:19.370
LISA LEE: Right.

00:12:19.370 --> 00:12:21.870
And so you often hear
people define their style.

00:12:21.870 --> 00:12:27.990
They saying I'm casual or
I like the bohemian look.

00:12:27.990 --> 00:12:28.950
Do you believe in that?

00:12:28.950 --> 00:12:31.950
Or do you feel like it's-- like
you talked about experimenting.

00:12:31.950 --> 00:12:35.460
And so what is behind
that definition

00:12:35.460 --> 00:12:38.049
and do you encourage women
to sort of throw that

00:12:38.049 --> 00:12:39.590
out the window and
say just wear what

00:12:39.590 --> 00:12:41.966
you feel is most comfortable
and defines you for the day?

00:12:41.966 --> 00:12:42.756
LUBOC AZRIA: Uh-uh.

00:12:42.756 --> 00:12:44.370
I think it depends
on your lifestyle.

00:12:44.370 --> 00:12:46.930
I think that most
of us-- I mean,

00:12:46.930 --> 00:12:48.540
it depends if you
want to blend in.

00:12:48.540 --> 00:12:51.972
Like, I think that women
should experiment with stuff.

00:12:51.972 --> 00:12:52.930
I think that's playing.

00:12:52.930 --> 00:12:55.549
Do you remember when we used
to play with clothes, dress-up,

00:12:55.549 --> 00:12:56.090
and all this?

00:12:56.090 --> 00:12:56.930
What happened to us?

00:12:56.930 --> 00:12:57.900
We stopped playing.

00:12:57.900 --> 00:13:00.200
We stopped experimenting.

00:13:00.200 --> 00:13:02.760
We stopped living.

00:13:02.760 --> 00:13:05.660
If you're taking fashion too
serious, you're doing it wrong.

00:13:05.660 --> 00:13:08.650
You're supposed to go in and try
every single thing in the store

00:13:08.650 --> 00:13:09.830
and have fun.

00:13:09.830 --> 00:13:12.840
Because women do not
dress based on trends.

00:13:12.840 --> 00:13:15.880
They dress based on
their body shape, period.

00:13:15.880 --> 00:13:18.260
You know what's going to
look good on you, right away.

00:13:18.260 --> 00:13:20.210
You don't need a
salesperson to tell you.

00:13:20.210 --> 00:13:22.625
So you know if you look
good in strapless dresses,

00:13:22.625 --> 00:13:23.750
you wear strapless dresses.

00:13:23.750 --> 00:13:25.916
If you look good in v-neck,
you look good in v-neck.

00:13:28.890 --> 00:13:30.130
That's because you know it.

00:13:30.130 --> 00:13:32.630
You put it on and it's right.

00:13:32.630 --> 00:13:35.789
And that's the difference.

00:13:35.789 --> 00:13:37.580
Comfort, obviously, is
extremely important.

00:13:37.580 --> 00:13:40.370
But you can be
elegantly comfortable.

00:13:40.370 --> 00:13:43.090
LISA LEE: So when you are
feeling a little down or maybe

00:13:43.090 --> 00:13:45.750
feeling you don't quite
have the confidence,

00:13:45.750 --> 00:13:48.700
what's your go-to outfit that
you'd sort of recommend people

00:13:48.700 --> 00:13:49.240
think about.

00:13:49.240 --> 00:13:55.132
LUBOC AZRIA: A really
big muumuu, sunglasses.

00:13:55.132 --> 00:13:56.910
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:56.910 --> 00:13:58.010
Yeah.

00:13:58.010 --> 00:14:03.166
Those are the days where
you're just having a good day.

00:14:03.166 --> 00:14:04.408
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:06.160 --> 00:14:07.190
I love muumuus.

00:14:07.190 --> 00:14:09.510
I have nothing against muumuus.

00:14:09.510 --> 00:14:11.142
They're great.

00:14:11.142 --> 00:14:13.225
LISA LEE: And so you talked
about your background,

00:14:13.225 --> 00:14:17.010
and your culture, and
dance, for instance.

00:14:17.010 --> 00:14:20.280
Has that influenced
your focus on comfort?

00:14:20.280 --> 00:14:21.710
Because obviously
as a dancer, you

00:14:21.710 --> 00:14:23.418
need to be able to
flow with the clothes.

00:14:23.418 --> 00:14:25.137
And how has that
influenced your life?

00:14:25.137 --> 00:14:27.470
LUBOC AZRIA: Well, I think
as a dancer, one thing that I

00:14:27.470 --> 00:14:28.640
learned is discipline.

00:14:28.640 --> 00:14:31.070
I think you have to be really
disciplined as a dancer

00:14:31.070 --> 00:14:32.620
and you have to be
very consistent.

00:14:32.620 --> 00:14:36.230
And the other thing I learned
how a woman's body moves.

00:14:36.230 --> 00:14:39.590
So I actually fit every
single garment in BCBG.

00:14:39.590 --> 00:14:42.460
There's nothing that leaves,
except for BCBCGeneration,

00:14:42.460 --> 00:14:45.910
but BCBGMAXAZRIA, or Herve
Leger, the Runway line,

00:14:45.910 --> 00:14:49.720
I actually physically
fit it on our fit model.

00:14:49.720 --> 00:14:51.600
And I go over all the details.

00:14:51.600 --> 00:14:53.550
And I actually put it
on myself, as well.

00:14:53.550 --> 00:14:55.050
Because I want to
know how it feels.

00:14:55.050 --> 00:14:57.220
Because I believe that
if you need alterations,

00:14:57.220 --> 00:14:59.630
then-- most women think
that there's something

00:14:59.630 --> 00:15:00.790
wrong with their bodies.

00:15:00.790 --> 00:15:02.040
There's nothing
wrong with your body.

00:15:02.040 --> 00:15:03.060
Your body is beautiful.

00:15:03.060 --> 00:15:06.690
There's something wrong
with the fit of the clothes.

00:15:06.690 --> 00:15:11.169
There's amazing brands out
there that have great quality

00:15:11.169 --> 00:15:11.960
and they look good.

00:15:11.960 --> 00:15:14.110
But you put it on
and you look dumpy.

00:15:14.110 --> 00:15:17.390
And understanding proportions
I think is very important.

00:15:17.390 --> 00:15:20.900
Understanding textures,
fabric, colors is important.

00:15:20.900 --> 00:15:23.230
So when I'm actually in the
fitting room-- by the way,

00:15:23.230 --> 00:15:26.690
my fit model is not
somebody who's very young.

00:15:26.690 --> 00:15:28.310
She's actually in her 50s.

00:15:28.310 --> 00:15:32.280
And the reason why is you can
take a beautiful, young model

00:15:32.280 --> 00:15:34.150
and everything is going
to look good on her.

00:15:34.150 --> 00:15:37.210
But you take a
50-year-old model and you

00:15:37.210 --> 00:15:41.440
try to make her look amazing,
that's the difference.

00:15:41.440 --> 00:15:43.520
And so I actually
do the opposite.

00:15:43.520 --> 00:15:46.940
I take something that I
think-- she's beautiful anyway.

00:15:46.940 --> 00:15:51.290
But it's just more of
appreciating what happens

00:15:51.290 --> 00:15:53.250
and where you need a lift.

00:15:53.250 --> 00:15:55.290
LISA LEE: And in terms
of comfort-- I mean,

00:15:55.290 --> 00:15:56.960
I think that's one
of the challenges.

00:15:56.960 --> 00:16:00.090
Like, I know for myself,
wearing heels, it looks great.

00:16:00.090 --> 00:16:01.530
I'd love to wear them every day.

00:16:01.530 --> 00:16:03.339
But it just doesn't
seem that comfortable.

00:16:03.339 --> 00:16:04.130
LUBOC AZRIA: Right.

00:16:04.130 --> 00:16:07.670
LISA LEE: What's your
recommendation for balancing

00:16:07.670 --> 00:16:09.412
practicality with style?

00:16:09.412 --> 00:16:11.120
LUBOC AZRIA: I think
it's the same thing.

00:16:11.120 --> 00:16:13.920
I think have a pair of shoes
with the heels in your bag.

00:16:13.920 --> 00:16:17.930
I mean, right now bags
looks suitcases anyway.

00:16:17.930 --> 00:16:20.760
I just think it's important--
like if you're in a meeting,

00:16:20.760 --> 00:16:22.260
it's nice to wear a heel.

00:16:22.260 --> 00:16:23.960
You're sitting down anyway.

00:16:23.960 --> 00:16:25.670
If you're running
around, obviously it's

00:16:25.670 --> 00:16:27.503
better to wear something
that's comfortable.

00:16:27.503 --> 00:16:28.830
I mean I run a marathon.

00:16:28.830 --> 00:16:31.118
So my feet grow a half
a size every time I run.

00:16:31.118 --> 00:16:32.118
It's getting ridiculous.

00:16:35.190 --> 00:16:36.860
Anyway, I like comfortable.

00:16:36.860 --> 00:16:39.510
I always have either flip-flops
or something in my bag,

00:16:39.510 --> 00:16:41.207
just so that I can relieve pain.

00:16:41.207 --> 00:16:43.290
But I have to tell you,
technology, let's talk it.

00:16:43.290 --> 00:16:45.420
You guys are in the head
of technology, right?

00:16:45.420 --> 00:16:49.490
Why can't we get little
massage pads inside the shoes

00:16:49.490 --> 00:16:50.491
so you can just plug-in?

00:16:50.491 --> 00:16:51.990
So when you're
sitting there, you're

00:16:51.990 --> 00:16:53.130
actually getting a massage.

00:16:53.130 --> 00:16:53.900
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:53.900 --> 00:16:56.020
I want to buy remote
control luggage.

00:16:56.020 --> 00:16:58.620
Can we talk about
when you're traveling?

00:16:58.620 --> 00:16:59.930
There's remote control cars.

00:16:59.930 --> 00:17:01.944
Why isn't there a
luggage remote control?

00:17:01.944 --> 00:17:02.860
LISA LEE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:17:03.220 --> 00:17:03.970
LUBOC AZRIA: Yeah.

00:17:03.970 --> 00:17:07.010
You just go, right?

00:17:07.010 --> 00:17:07.839
I'm serious.

00:17:07.839 --> 00:17:09.630
There's so much to invent.

00:17:09.630 --> 00:17:11.270
I was sitting and
having a conversation

00:17:11.270 --> 00:17:12.010
with someone yesterday.

00:17:12.010 --> 00:17:14.468
And they were talking about
all this technology for clothes

00:17:14.468 --> 00:17:16.930
and your clothes can
light up in the dark.

00:17:16.930 --> 00:17:20.730
And I thought, well, OK.

00:17:20.730 --> 00:17:24.230
If you have a purpose for
that, I think it's important.

00:17:24.230 --> 00:17:28.590
But there's so much innovation
in textiles right now.

00:17:28.590 --> 00:17:30.260
There's fabrics that
make you feel good.

00:17:30.260 --> 00:17:32.700
They have a little bit of
copper in it and something else.

00:17:32.700 --> 00:17:34.950
I mean there's so
much innovation.

00:17:34.950 --> 00:17:36.120
It's very exciting.

00:17:36.120 --> 00:17:38.560
Because the clothes are supposed
to protect you, and make

00:17:38.560 --> 00:17:42.570
you feel beautiful, and
make you feel comfortable.

00:17:42.570 --> 00:17:44.710
But not everywhere do you
want to be comfortable.

00:17:44.710 --> 00:17:46.126
Remember, the
moment you're really

00:17:46.126 --> 00:17:49.600
comfortable that means
that you're not living,

00:17:49.600 --> 00:17:50.340
you're existing.

00:17:50.340 --> 00:17:53.052
Like, it's nice to be a little
bit uncomfortable in everything

00:17:53.052 --> 00:17:54.760
because that's how
you're moving forward.

00:17:54.760 --> 00:17:56.156
Think about it.

00:17:56.156 --> 00:17:57.530
If you're too
comfortable, you're

00:17:57.530 --> 00:17:59.860
not probably producing what
you could be producing.

00:17:59.860 --> 00:18:01.210
If you have a little
discomfort-- like,

00:18:01.210 --> 00:18:02.751
I'm always looking
at the collection.

00:18:02.751 --> 00:18:05.500
And if it's too
perfect, I'm like, no.

00:18:05.500 --> 00:18:08.030
Something is really
wrong with that.

00:18:08.030 --> 00:18:10.000
LISA LEE: It's motto we
live by here at Google.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:13.620
Always try things that are-- or
always uncomfortably excited.

00:18:13.620 --> 00:18:14.940
LUBOC AZRIA: Absolutely.

00:18:14.940 --> 00:18:20.590
I think that's how you live,
and you grow, and you evolve.

00:18:20.590 --> 00:18:22.573
Complacency doesn't
get you anywhere.

00:18:22.573 --> 00:18:23.420
LISA LEE: Right.

00:18:23.420 --> 00:18:25.600
So talking about technology,
I'd love to ask you,

00:18:25.600 --> 00:18:28.840
do you have a favorite
Google product?

00:18:28.840 --> 00:18:30.000
LUBOC AZRIA: Yes.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:33.340
Google Image Search,
can't live without it.

00:18:33.340 --> 00:18:35.570
Yes.

00:18:35.570 --> 00:18:36.330
Absolutely.

00:18:36.330 --> 00:18:38.200
LISA LEE: And how do you use it
and how does it influence you?

00:18:38.200 --> 00:18:40.530
LUBOC AZRIA: Every day, I
just literally with research

00:18:40.530 --> 00:18:41.090
for images.

00:18:41.090 --> 00:18:43.520
I remember we used
to go to libraries

00:18:43.520 --> 00:18:47.640
and sign the books out, and
bring them, and then copy them,

00:18:47.640 --> 00:18:49.150
and then put them in folders.

00:18:49.150 --> 00:18:51.761
I mean I don't
throw away anything.

00:18:51.761 --> 00:18:54.220
It's a really bad idea.

00:18:54.220 --> 00:18:56.130
And so now, it's amazing.

00:18:56.130 --> 00:18:59.880
You can just really find
anything, save it, use it,

00:18:59.880 --> 00:19:00.457
print it out.

00:19:00.457 --> 00:19:02.790
I mean we will make the most
amazing inspiration boards.

00:19:02.790 --> 00:19:04.470
It's fantastic.

00:19:04.470 --> 00:19:05.610
LISA LEE: Yeah.

00:19:05.610 --> 00:19:07.350
And what about in
terms of social media?

00:19:07.350 --> 00:19:12.350
I mean I think there's
Twitter, there's Instagram,

00:19:12.350 --> 00:19:14.480
there's Google Social.

00:19:14.480 --> 00:19:17.700
How do you use that to
connect with your customers

00:19:17.700 --> 00:19:19.890
and to get to know them better?

00:19:19.890 --> 00:19:25.010
LUBOC AZRIA: Well, I remember
when we did our first runway

00:19:25.010 --> 00:19:30.820
show in 1996, in New York,
people didn't know who we were.

00:19:30.820 --> 00:19:33.110
And we were the first
contemporary company

00:19:33.110 --> 00:19:36.430
to show during the Fashion Week
in New York with designers.

00:19:36.430 --> 00:19:38.510
And I don't know if you
know the whole idea?

00:19:38.510 --> 00:19:41.010
Design is really a price point.

00:19:41.010 --> 00:19:41.940
That's all it is.

00:19:41.940 --> 00:19:43.780
Everything is designed.

00:19:43.780 --> 00:19:45.650
There's no product
that's made generically.

00:19:45.650 --> 00:19:48.210
Even a t-shirt, I think
t-shirts are the hardest things

00:19:48.210 --> 00:19:51.350
to fit anyway because you
need to get that fit right.

00:19:51.350 --> 00:19:55.270
Anyway, going back to--
so whoever reviewed us,

00:19:55.270 --> 00:19:56.840
defined us.

00:19:56.840 --> 00:19:58.700
And they put us
into a certain box.

00:19:58.700 --> 00:20:00.820
And there's nothing
we can do about it.

00:20:00.820 --> 00:20:02.890
Because at that time,
there was no social media

00:20:02.890 --> 00:20:04.980
to tell you a story,
to tell your message,

00:20:04.980 --> 00:20:08.030
to inspire, to
connect, to really

00:20:08.030 --> 00:20:10.900
make the consumer
or your audience

00:20:10.900 --> 00:20:14.830
understand you as a
company, your DNA.

00:20:14.830 --> 00:20:17.650
So I feel that social media
now, it is incredible.

00:20:17.650 --> 00:20:18.600
We tell our stories.

00:20:18.600 --> 00:20:19.680
We tell our passions.

00:20:19.680 --> 00:20:20.710
We connect.

00:20:20.710 --> 00:20:24.860
Whether it's Twitter, or
Pinterest, or Instagram,

00:20:24.860 --> 00:20:27.110
whatever it is, we're
telling stories.

00:20:27.110 --> 00:20:29.820
And they're curated because
it's our point of view.

00:20:29.820 --> 00:20:32.860
That's how we would
want to see things done.

00:20:32.860 --> 00:20:34.520
And I think you
see the aesthetics.

00:20:34.520 --> 00:20:36.100
You see our sensibility.

00:20:36.100 --> 00:20:37.130
You see your passion.

00:20:37.130 --> 00:20:39.130
You see our creativity.

00:20:39.130 --> 00:20:40.540
You see who we connect to.

00:20:40.540 --> 00:20:44.070
And that's unique to each brand.

00:20:44.070 --> 00:20:46.080
And I love that
everybody's on social.

00:20:46.080 --> 00:20:46.820
I really do.

00:20:46.820 --> 00:20:48.480
And I love the Twitter.

00:20:48.480 --> 00:20:50.660
I love that you
can send messages

00:20:50.660 --> 00:20:55.270
to the world about what
you're doing and connect.

00:20:55.270 --> 00:20:56.270
LISA LEE: That's great.

00:20:56.270 --> 00:21:01.460
And so how does that influence--
in terms of, like, design,

00:21:01.460 --> 00:21:04.140
like do you ever think
about, oh, someone's

00:21:04.140 --> 00:21:05.570
given me this great idea.

00:21:05.570 --> 00:21:05.960
LUBOC AZRIA: Absolutely.

00:21:05.960 --> 00:21:07.770
LISA LEE: And we need to move
sort of a different direction

00:21:07.770 --> 00:21:09.260
that what we were
originally thinking.

00:21:09.260 --> 00:21:09.980
Does that happen?

00:21:09.980 --> 00:21:10.730
LUBOC AZRIA: Yeah.

00:21:13.620 --> 00:21:17.710
So what usually happens is
that we get a suggestion

00:21:17.710 --> 00:21:18.790
and we meet people.

00:21:18.790 --> 00:21:22.190
I'm very big about meeting
people and understanding

00:21:22.190 --> 00:21:23.346
their needs.

00:21:23.346 --> 00:21:25.220
Because obviously, we
don't create everything

00:21:25.220 --> 00:21:26.100
for ourselves.

00:21:26.100 --> 00:21:27.380
But there is a definite need.

00:21:27.380 --> 00:21:31.190
So through social media
we have, we love our fans.

00:21:31.190 --> 00:21:34.980
Or we have a Week
of Chic or things

00:21:34.980 --> 00:21:37.590
that we do to really get
closer and understand

00:21:37.590 --> 00:21:41.010
what our fans like.

00:21:41.010 --> 00:21:44.480
And so I think in terms
of ideas, I don't know.

00:21:44.480 --> 00:21:47.250
