Self-expression,
how difficult it

00:22:26.060 --> 00:22:29.170
is when you actually step away
from it and put it on a wall.

00:22:29.170 --> 00:22:30.810
So I think art to
me is very personal.

00:22:30.810 --> 00:22:32.320
And what we connect
to is personal.

00:22:32.320 --> 00:22:33.450
So that's a huge influence.

00:22:33.450 --> 00:22:36.220
Travel is great.

00:22:36.220 --> 00:22:37.980
You know, textiles.

00:22:37.980 --> 00:22:40.190
People, I work with
the most creative,

00:22:40.190 --> 00:22:42.490
amazing, innovative people.

00:22:42.490 --> 00:22:43.850
And I'm obsessed with them.

00:22:43.850 --> 00:22:45.766
And most of the time,
they come up with ideas.

00:22:45.766 --> 00:22:48.290
And I'm just like,
oh, I'm not so sure.

00:22:48.290 --> 00:22:48.790
[LAUGHTER]

00:22:48.790 --> 00:22:51.770
And really, I love it.

00:22:51.770 --> 00:22:53.840
No, I think it's really
working with the team

00:22:53.840 --> 00:22:55.380
and really kind of connecting.

00:22:55.380 --> 00:22:58.490
And I think they bring a lot of
ideas and then we share ideas.

00:22:58.490 --> 00:23:02.530
My overall job is
not just to design,

00:23:02.530 --> 00:23:05.650
it's to really bring clarity.

00:23:05.650 --> 00:23:08.820
Because if we throw
everything against the wall

00:23:08.820 --> 00:23:11.550
and see what sticks,
it takes too long.

00:23:11.550 --> 00:23:15.010
I'm almost like, I
edit a point of view

00:23:15.010 --> 00:23:17.990
to make sure that-- it's
one thing being creative.

00:23:17.990 --> 00:23:19.790
It's another thing
being successful.

00:23:19.790 --> 00:23:21.510
We create for a woman.

00:23:21.510 --> 00:23:23.920
And we want her
to feel beautiful.

00:23:23.920 --> 00:23:27.220
And obviously, we're not
going to do three sleeves

00:23:27.220 --> 00:23:30.170
or we're not going to make
her look like a clown.

00:23:30.170 --> 00:23:34.960
And I always want a woman
to look a certain way.

00:23:34.960 --> 00:23:37.420
A woman always wants
to look taller,

00:23:37.420 --> 00:23:39.625
and slimmer, and more elegant.

00:23:39.625 --> 00:23:41.000
LISA LEE: It sounds
like you work

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:42.520
with a lot of
inspirational women.

00:23:42.520 --> 00:23:43.345
LUBOC AZRIA: I do.

00:23:43.345 --> 00:23:46.600
LISA LEE: And so for yourself,
you've become very successful.

00:23:46.600 --> 00:23:48.920
Any advice you'd give to
the women in the audience

00:23:48.920 --> 00:23:51.490
about becoming a leader in your
space, and sort of the path

00:23:51.490 --> 00:23:55.220
that you took, and
the characteristics I

00:23:55.220 --> 00:23:57.590
think that you find most
important in leaders?

00:23:57.590 --> 00:23:58.590
LUBOC AZRIA: Absolutely.

00:23:58.590 --> 00:24:01.580
I think we need to
define what success is.

00:24:01.580 --> 00:24:05.190
Success to me is
doing what you love,

00:24:05.190 --> 00:24:08.300
and having passion, and living
your life so that you're

00:24:08.300 --> 00:24:09.720
exhaustive about passion.

00:24:09.720 --> 00:24:12.360
That to me, is truly success.

00:24:12.360 --> 00:24:13.820
In terms of being
a leader, I think

00:24:13.820 --> 00:24:15.430
it's surrounding
yourself with people

00:24:15.430 --> 00:24:17.654
who are better than you are.

00:24:17.654 --> 00:24:19.445
That takes strength
and that takes courage.

00:24:21.990 --> 00:24:23.940
People are everything.

00:24:23.940 --> 00:24:25.214
We work in a community.

00:24:25.214 --> 00:24:26.880
And you really have
to surround yourself

00:24:26.880 --> 00:24:28.338
with people who
bring out the best.

00:24:28.338 --> 00:24:30.954
And in terms of leadership,
live by example.

00:24:30.954 --> 00:24:33.370
If you challenge somebody,
they have to do that, make sure

00:24:33.370 --> 00:24:34.980
you can do it as well.

00:24:34.980 --> 00:24:36.650
And I think that's important.

00:24:36.650 --> 00:24:39.460
People don't work for a company.

00:24:39.460 --> 00:24:42.280
People work for other people.

00:24:42.280 --> 00:24:45.220
And I think it's important as
a leader to be true to that,

00:24:45.220 --> 00:24:50.170
to be honest, to
lead by example,

00:24:50.170 --> 00:24:54.180
and collaborate with people,
give people opportunities.

00:24:54.180 --> 00:24:56.750
I think that's so important.

00:24:56.750 --> 00:24:59.160
And I have just a quote.

00:24:59.160 --> 00:25:02.030
I have this amazing quote
for all of you females,

00:25:02.030 --> 00:25:03.990
by Madeleine Albright.

00:25:03.990 --> 00:25:08.670
Because she said, "Women
who do not help other women

00:25:08.670 --> 00:25:11.164
have a special place in hell."

00:25:11.164 --> 00:25:12.480
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:12.480 --> 00:25:16.820
And the reason why she said that
is because a majority of women,

00:25:16.820 --> 00:25:20.520
they are not CEOs, or CFOs
or at the top of the-- I

00:25:20.520 --> 00:25:23.970
call it the food chain-- is
because other woman sabotaged

00:25:23.970 --> 00:25:26.780
them, not men.

00:25:26.780 --> 00:25:28.110
Women sabotage women.

00:25:28.110 --> 00:25:32.730
So if we stop doing that, there
will be more leaders out there.

00:25:32.730 --> 00:25:35.620
And our goal-- I mean
we have a whole program.

00:25:35.620 --> 00:25:38.430
It's called Contributor
Program, that I

00:25:38.430 --> 00:25:39.710
think is extremely important.

00:25:39.710 --> 00:25:42.500
So it takes women that
perhaps are not in the news,

00:25:42.500 --> 00:25:47.087
or women who are just incredible
leaders in their own rights.

00:25:47.087 --> 00:25:47.920
I wrote their names.

00:25:47.920 --> 00:25:51.100
It was Padma Warrior, who
is with Cisco Systems.

00:25:51.100 --> 00:25:53.350
She is beyond amazing.

00:25:53.350 --> 00:25:55.510
She was one of our
first contributors.

00:25:55.510 --> 00:25:58.970
And I loved her strength,
her passion, her vision,

00:25:58.970 --> 00:26:01.480
and how she made it
to the top with just

00:26:01.480 --> 00:26:02.580
caring about other people.

00:26:02.580 --> 00:26:03.913
She never thought about herself.

00:26:03.913 --> 00:26:06.180
Do you know what I'm saying,
always doing by example.

00:26:06.180 --> 00:26:09.230
I have another female, Claire
Rothman, who is amazing.

00:26:09.230 --> 00:26:12.870
She is 86 years old.

00:26:12.870 --> 00:26:15.570
She was the head of
Forum, an amazing woman,

00:26:15.570 --> 00:26:16.710
and how they did it.

00:26:16.710 --> 00:26:19.430
And they did it through
recognizing other women,

00:26:19.430 --> 00:26:23.690
never stabbing anybody in
the back, caring for people,

00:26:23.690 --> 00:26:25.260
understanding,
following through.

00:26:25.260 --> 00:26:26.780
And I think that's
true leadership.

