00:41:01.345 --> 00:41:03.912
and we can go shopping.

00:41:03.912 --> 00:41:06.120
I wanted to make sure we
left some time for questions

00:41:06.120 --> 00:41:08.950
from the audience, if
anybody has any for Luboc?

00:41:08.950 --> 00:41:11.280
AUDIENCE: Since you
joined the company in 1991

00:41:11.280 --> 00:41:16.267
and it have been to 2015 now,
has the vision for the company

00:41:16.267 --> 00:41:19.130
kind of changed?

00:41:19.130 --> 00:41:22.816
And how are you actually
contributing to driving it?

00:41:22.816 --> 00:41:27.684
And what's your corporate
story, a little bit?

00:41:27.684 --> 00:41:28.850
LUBOC AZRIA: It has changed.

00:41:28.850 --> 00:41:29.849
Well, it hasn't changed.

00:41:29.849 --> 00:41:30.930
It has evolved.

00:41:30.930 --> 00:41:36.060
I think that in the beginning,
the difference between BCBG

00:41:36.060 --> 00:41:38.740
and another company,
it is design-driven.

00:41:38.740 --> 00:41:40.490
It's not merchant-driven.

00:41:40.490 --> 00:41:42.320
Do you guys know the
difference between it?

00:41:42.320 --> 00:41:47.350
So merchant-driven, it is like
a GAP, or Banana Republic,

00:41:47.350 --> 00:41:50.640
or companies that sort of
produce based on the new units.

00:41:50.640 --> 00:41:54.570
Like, it's a little bit
more-- it's different.

00:41:54.570 --> 00:41:56.180
Design, we're design-driven.

00:41:56.180 --> 00:42:00.010
So basically we create
things that we want to wear.

00:42:00.010 --> 00:42:02.330
So it's very different.

00:42:02.330 --> 00:42:07.084
So with the times-- and we've
seen economically what happens.

00:42:07.084 --> 00:42:08.250
Do you know what I'm saying?

00:42:08.250 --> 00:42:11.730
So you have to always change
and evolve a little bit.

00:42:11.730 --> 00:42:14.290
At one point, we
had 20 divisions.

00:42:14.290 --> 00:42:16.910
Then we went to,
like, six divisions.

00:42:16.910 --> 00:42:19.170
So you're constantly
trying different things.

00:42:19.170 --> 00:42:21.920
When we originally
started BCBG-- well,

00:42:21.920 --> 00:42:24.590
Max started BCBG,
let me clarify this.

00:42:24.590 --> 00:42:27.250
He started BCBG in 1989.

00:42:27.250 --> 00:42:31.200
When I joined the company
in 1991, Max at the time

00:42:31.200 --> 00:42:32.440
was doing item business.

00:42:32.440 --> 00:42:34.450
He was doing pleated
skirts, stirrup pants.

00:42:34.450 --> 00:42:36.120
He wasn't doing collections.

00:42:36.120 --> 00:42:38.250
When I joined the
company, I realized

00:42:38.250 --> 00:42:39.570
that there's a huge void.

00:42:39.570 --> 00:42:43.710
At that time, there was
either Donna Karan at the top

00:42:43.710 --> 00:42:46.790
or there was Casual Corner.

00:42:46.790 --> 00:42:48.470
There was nothing in between.

00:42:48.470 --> 00:42:51.340
I mean you had a white
space that was so-- I

00:42:51.340 --> 00:42:55.420
didn't understand how you cannot
make clothes in the between

00:42:55.420 --> 00:42:56.060
range.

00:42:56.060 --> 00:42:59.550
So we were one of the first
contemporary companies,

00:42:59.550 --> 00:43:02.710
basically in America, to
create that type of fashion.

00:43:02.710 --> 00:43:06.650
With time, more people started
going in that territory.

00:43:06.650 --> 00:43:10.950
So you had to kind of
decide which other places.

00:43:10.950 --> 00:43:13.540
You're constantly
looking for voids.

00:43:13.540 --> 00:43:17.590
And once you realize that a
woman dresses based on her body

00:43:17.590 --> 00:43:19.610
shape, not based on
trends, you start

00:43:19.610 --> 00:43:22.040
creating clothes
that are versatile,

00:43:22.040 --> 00:43:25.020
that are right
for her lifestyle.

00:43:25.020 --> 00:43:26.440
So you kind of evolve it.

00:43:26.440 --> 00:43:29.590
So I don't believe in
one particular formula.

00:43:29.590 --> 00:43:32.550
I believe you are changing,
evolving, and growing.

00:43:32.550 --> 00:43:35.110
So with my position
in the company

00:43:35.110 --> 00:43:37.197
I think-- when I became
creative director.

00:43:37.197 --> 00:43:38.780
Now, I'm more involved
with marketing.

00:43:38.780 --> 00:43:40.946
So you have other departments
start reporting to you

00:43:40.946 --> 00:43:44.730
because your vision
is so direct.

00:43:44.730 --> 00:43:47.940
So one thing in fashion is you
don't want to be anybody else.

00:43:47.940 --> 00:43:49.910
Your DNA defines you.

00:43:49.910 --> 00:43:55.220
Like, for example, Herve
Leger has a very distinct DNA.

00:43:55.220 --> 00:43:58.910
And I'm not going to start
doing something for them

00:43:58.910 --> 00:44:01.610
that I think out that alignment.

00:44:01.610 --> 00:44:05.810
With BCBG as well, I
will not do-- like, I've

00:44:05.810 --> 00:44:07.383
been trying to do jeans though.

00:44:10.140 --> 00:44:13.150
But I will always stick to
making a woman feel and look

00:44:13.150 --> 00:44:13.910
beautiful.

00:44:13.910 --> 00:44:16.010
I will not make clothes
that sort of doesn't

00:44:16.010 --> 00:44:17.100
do that and evolve.

00:44:17.100 --> 00:44:18.840
But my position the
company has grown

00:44:18.840 --> 00:44:21.760
in terms of how many departments
report to me, which makes it

00:44:21.760 --> 00:44:24.940
very little time for me.

00:44:24.940 --> 00:44:26.614
LISA LEE: More demands.

00:44:26.614 --> 00:44:29.030
LUBOC AZRIA: Just a little.

00:44:29.030 --> 00:44:31.660
AUDIENCE: My question is more
on the career development side.

00:44:31.660 --> 00:44:33.800
So obviously, we
all work in tech.

00:44:33.800 --> 00:44:36.540
And it can be more of a
male-dominated industry.

00:44:36.540 --> 00:44:39.030
And so I'm wondering
what your experience is

00:44:39.030 --> 00:44:43.990
like as a female leader in
such a female-centric industry?

00:44:43.990 --> 00:44:48.020
And what that looks like as
you kind of rose in the ranks.

00:44:48.020 --> 00:44:51.520
And what that looks like now
as maybe a female community,

00:44:51.520 --> 00:44:54.380
where, like you were
saying, you're employing

00:44:54.380 --> 00:44:56.550
future female leaders?

00:44:56.550 --> 00:44:59.010
LUBOC AZRIA: Well, my
situation is very different.

00:44:59.010 --> 00:45:01.770
Don't forget that I
actually married Max.

00:45:01.770 --> 00:45:04.101
So I was already on
top of food chain.

00:45:04.101 --> 00:45:05.484
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:06.410 --> 00:45:11.970
But I have to say that I
really-- I wanted to learn.

00:45:18.320 --> 00:45:20.760
The one thing I've
learned is fashion

00:45:20.760 --> 00:45:23.610
is still very male dominated.

00:45:23.610 --> 00:45:26.600
The bankers, the real estate,
everything, it's very male

00:45:26.600 --> 00:45:27.100
dominated.

00:45:27.100 --> 00:45:36.770
I think what you need to do is
really be there, be honest, do

00:45:36.770 --> 00:45:39.590
more than you need to do.

00:45:39.590 --> 00:45:42.410
And I think it's being
present, communicate well.

00:45:42.410 --> 00:45:46.730
I mean men are very
simple creatures.

00:45:46.730 --> 00:45:49.460
And I'll explain to you
why they are simple.

00:45:49.460 --> 00:45:55.480
Because we bring men--
women create men.

00:45:55.480 --> 00:45:57.370
And we bring them up.

00:45:57.370 --> 00:45:59.880
And all they need
is significance.

00:45:59.880 --> 00:46:01.720
You tell them that
they look good,

00:46:01.720 --> 00:46:05.450
you tell them that they do well,
that the projects that they did

00:46:05.450 --> 00:46:06.360
were great.

00:46:06.360 --> 00:46:07.960
You align with them.

00:46:07.960 --> 00:46:09.915
And you see the
results happening.

00:46:09.915 --> 00:46:11.170
Do you know what I'm saying?

00:46:11.170 --> 00:46:17.900
Like I said, you just have to--
they're not your-- you just

00:46:17.900 --> 00:46:20.000
communicate well.

00:46:20.000 --> 00:46:20.900
And that's it.

00:46:20.900 --> 00:46:21.800
You communicate well.

00:46:21.800 --> 00:46:23.370
You be open to their ideas.

00:46:23.370 --> 00:46:25.600
You show them your ideas.

00:46:25.600 --> 00:46:30.120
Before I was at BCBG, I
worked for a designer.

00:46:30.120 --> 00:46:35.150
And I remember leaving sketches
every single day on her desk.

00:46:35.150 --> 00:46:36.780
She didn't want any help.

00:46:36.780 --> 00:46:38.460
But I would leave
it just because I

00:46:38.460 --> 00:46:39.790
thought this was a great idea.

00:46:39.790 --> 00:46:42.910
This was a great
idea, maybe this.

00:46:42.910 --> 00:46:44.690
We like to see passion.

00:46:44.690 --> 00:46:46.640
We like to see people
who want to do more.

00:46:46.640 --> 00:46:47.670
We like to do that.

00:46:47.670 --> 00:46:51.000
And with that, you
can really grow.

00:46:51.000 --> 00:46:53.850
Nowadays, I think
everybody is always

00:46:53.850 --> 00:46:56.880
looking for that next
talent, that next person

00:46:56.880 --> 00:46:58.660
with great ideas, innovation.

00:46:58.660 --> 00:47:01.390
And also put yourself
always-- if you think about

00:47:01.390 --> 00:47:04.160
me, me, me, me, you're
never going to get there.

00:47:04.160 --> 00:47:08.470
Like if I'm creating
clothes to make money,

00:47:08.470 --> 00:47:11.160
I will fail every single day.

00:47:11.160 --> 00:47:12.730
You have to have
a greater purpose.

00:47:12.730 --> 00:47:18.260
So if your purpose is to
get a higher level position,

00:47:18.260 --> 00:47:20.190
then you need to read
the job description.

00:47:20.190 --> 00:47:21.940
You guys don't have
job descriptions here.

00:47:21.940 --> 00:47:24.380
But you have to see what
that person is doing

00:47:24.380 --> 00:47:26.934
and what they're excelling at.

00:47:26.934 --> 00:47:28.100
Do you know what I'm saying?

00:47:28.100 --> 00:47:30.810
And then you see, can
I actually do that?

00:47:30.810 --> 00:47:33.610
We talked earlier about success.

00:47:33.610 --> 00:47:38.000
And it's very lonely at the top.

00:47:38.000 --> 00:47:40.460
And if you're the
type of person that

00:47:40.460 --> 00:47:44.360
likes to connect with people,
collaborate, and be together,

00:47:44.360 --> 00:47:46.110
and the whole thing,
at the top sometimes,

00:47:46.110 --> 00:47:51.800
when you have to
make every decision--

00:47:51.800 --> 00:47:54.540
it's not always
right for everyone.

00:47:54.540 --> 00:47:56.420
I just want to just
put it out there.

00:47:56.420 --> 00:47:58.340
As a woman, we like
to collaborate.

00:47:58.340 --> 00:47:59.189
We like to share.

00:47:59.189 --> 00:48:00.480
We like to do different things.

00:48:00.480 --> 00:48:02.400
At the top, it's
kind of you have to--

00:48:02.400 --> 00:48:04.120
Like my husband, a
lot of times, he'll

00:48:04.120 --> 00:48:06.560
make decisions that I
totally disagree with.

00:48:06.560 --> 00:48:09.140
But I'll sit there and
I'll talk to him about it.

00:48:09.140 --> 00:48:12.640
I'll have him explain to me
why he made the decision so I

00:48:12.640 --> 00:48:16.190
can better support his vision.

00:48:16.190 --> 00:48:17.660
And that's what
makes a difference,

00:48:17.660 --> 00:48:19.570
not just saying, OK, I'll do it.

00:48:19.570 --> 00:48:20.070
No.

00:48:20.070 --> 00:48:20.950
Don't just do it.

00:48:20.950 --> 00:48:23.296
You understand the whole--
like the difference

00:48:23.296 --> 00:48:24.670
between, I think,
a lot of people

